exports[`caseStudyToMarkdown — snapshots > EN · ai-warehouse 1`] = `
"# AI Warehouse · Demo stock ops

\`02 · ai-warehouse · Demo\`

Fictional inventory assistant that turns receipt photos and operator notes into reviewable stock operations with weighted-cost math and rollback records.

**Scope:** Demo · 5 weeks equivalent  
**Role:** Operational inventory workflow with AI-assisted drafts

**Video:** [YouTube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dQw4w9WgXcQ) · [RuTube](https://rutube.ru/video/private/2afc367fc1968ed386e52665ee7a829b/?p=WcFMiE-n0wydU96W_9-nXw)

## Video walkthrough

Demo warehouse walkthrough: AI extracts a draft from a receipt photo, the operator reviews it in the WebApp, and weighted-average cost recalculates only after confirmation. Original evidence stays attached to every proposal.

Demo placeholder transcript. The video walks through the public warehouse demo — receipt intake, draft review, server-side cost math, rollback records. Replace this transcript when forking the engine with your own content.

---

## Context

> A receipt is not an order. It is a draft until review.

Inventory teams often collect messy inputs: receipt photos, supplier messages, and short notes from a busy shift. The useful AI job is to normalize that input into draft operations without bypassing stock integrity.

The demo keeps arithmetic server-owned. Weighted-cost updates, ingredient usage, and negative-stock checks happen after the draft is reviewed, not inside the model response.

## Facts

| | |
|---|---|
| **Surface** | Stock operations dashboard |
| **Inputs** | Receipt image · manual note · supplier text |
| **Review** | Supply · deduction · preparation lanes |
| **Safety** | Server-side validation before commit |

## Architecture

### Draft-to-confirm flow

\`\`\`text
Image / note -> parse draft -> operator review -> validate -> commit
                     |             | edit / reject |           |
                     v             v               v           v
                raw evidence   proposal log    domain checks  stock rows
\`\`\`

**Evidence.** The original input stays attached to the operation.

**Math.** The model can suggest fields; the backend recomputes totals.

## Key engineering decisions

### 01 · Evidence stays beside the draft

**Decision.** Every proposed operation keeps the source image or note until it is confirmed or rejected.

**Why.** Operators need to compare AI extraction against the original input.

**Cost.** Storage grows faster, but review quality is visible.

### 02 · Server-owned cost math

**Decision.** Weighted average cost and stock deltas are recomputed by the backend.

**Why.** A language model should not be the source of truth for accounting arithmetic.

**Cost.** The UI must explain mismatches between model draft and validated values.

### 03 · Rollback as a product surface

**Decision.** Confirmed operations can be reversed through typed correction records.

**Why.** Operational software must support mistakes without silent database edits.

**Cost.** Reporting queries need to account for corrections.

## Stack

| | |
|---|---|
| **Backend** | FastAPI · PostgreSQL · validation layer |
| **AI intake** | OCR · structured extraction · confidence hints |
| **Frontend** | React review lanes · diffable fields |
| **Workers** | Async image processing · retry queue |
| **Audit** | Raw evidence · proposals · corrections |
| **Demo media** | Generic SVG placeholder assets |

## Lessons & status

### Carry forward

- Draft and evidence must stay linked.
- Accounting math belongs outside the model.
- Rollback records beat manual database repairs.

### Would change

- Add bulk review only after single-item review is trusted.
- Expose validation errors earlier in the draft state.
- Keep image preprocessing reproducible for debugging.

Fictionalized case used to stress long-form operational copy.

---

Source: https://ilyadev.xyz/cases/ai-warehouse (HTML) · /cases/ai-warehouse.txt (this file)
Previous: 01 — AI CRM · Demo lead desk → https://ilyadev.xyz/cases/ai-crm.txt
Up next: 03 — AI Video Editor · Demo timeline → https://ilyadev.xyz/cases/ai-video-editor.txt
Index: https://ilyadev.xyz/llms.txt — full case-study list
Author: Demo Author — https://ilyadev.xyz/index.txt
"
`;

exports[`caseStudyToMarkdown — snapshots > EN · macos-vpn 1`] = `
"# macOS Network Guard · Demo client

\`05 · macos-vpn · Demo\`

Fictional macOS menu-bar client that models per-app network policy, connection state, and kill-switch behavior without shipping private infrastructure details.

**Scope:** Demo · desktop systems  
**Role:** Desktop network-control demo with explicit failure states

---

## Context

> Network tools fail. Product must show what state failed.

The fictional client focuses on the user-facing side of a network-control product: state clarity, predictable app policy, and failure modes that do not silently expose traffic.

Private endpoints, keys, and provider details are intentionally absent. The public case keeps the system shape: a menu-bar surface, a connection state machine, policy storage, and guardrails around unsafe transitions.

## Facts

| | |
|---|---|
| **Surface** | macOS menu-bar utility |
| **Policy** | Per-app allow/block routing model |
| **State** | Disconnected · connecting · protected · degraded · blocked |
| **Safety** | Kill-switch state is visible, not silent |

## Architecture

### Connection state model

\`\`\`text
connect -> connecting -> protected
   |            | error        | tunnel lost
   v            v              v
blocked <- degraded <- reconnect attempt
\`\`\`

**Blocked.** Unsafe traffic stays blocked until the user or policy exits.

**UI.** Every state maps to one visible label and one allowed action set.

## Key engineering decisions

### 01 · State machine before UI polish

**Decision.** Connection state is modeled as explicit states with allowed transitions.

**Why.** Network products fail in edges; implicit booleans hide those edges.

**Cost.** More up-front modeling before the interface looks finished.

### 02 · Policy is separate from session

**Decision.** Per-app routing policy is stored apart from the active connection session.

**Why.** Users should be able to edit policy without mutating current tunnel state accidentally.

**Cost.** The UI must explain pending vs active policy clearly.

### 03 · Unsafe state stays visible

**Decision.** Kill-switch activation is shown as a first-class blocked state.

**Why.** A security feature that hides itself creates support debt and user confusion.

**Cost.** More copy and edge-case handling in the menu-bar surface.

## Stack

| | |
|---|---|
| **App** | SwiftUI-style menu-bar surface |
| **Network** | NetworkExtension concepts · guarded tunnel state |
| **Policy** | Per-app routing table · persisted preferences |
| **Helper** | Signed helper model · privileged boundary notes |
| **Testing** | State transition fixtures · disconnect scenarios |
| **Privacy** | No private endpoints, keys, or real client media |

## Lessons & status

### Carry forward

- Explicit states beat boolean connection flags.
- Policy editing needs a separate mental model from active sessions.
- Unsafe network behavior must be visible.

### Would change

- Model degraded mode before designing icons.
- Keep provider-specific logic behind a narrow adapter.
- Write failure copy while implementing the state machine.

Fictionalized desktop case for public repo review.

---

Source: https://ilyadev.xyz/cases/macos-vpn (HTML) · /cases/macos-vpn.txt (this file)
Previous: 04 — Roblox Arena · Demo runtime → https://ilyadev.xyz/cases/roblox-game.txt
Up next: 06 — Portfolio Engine · Public repo case → https://ilyadev.xyz/cases/portfolio-site.txt
Index: https://ilyadev.xyz/llms.txt — full case-study list
Author: Demo Author — https://ilyadev.xyz/index.txt
"
`;

exports[`caseStudyToMarkdown — snapshots > EN · portfolio-site 1`] = `
"# Portfolio Engine · Public repo case

\`06 · portfolio-site · Open engine\`

The real architecture case for this repository: typed bilingual content, route-aware case pages, text mirrors for agents, and privacy-first analytics.

**Scope:** Production engine · public demo content  
**Role:** Frontend architecture, content system, telemetry, and static publishing

---

## Context

> Portfolio as resume is weak. Portfolio as auditable system is stronger.

The project started as a portfolio page and became a small publishing engine. That is intentional: the site is both a resume surface and a proof artifact that another engineer can clone, inspect, and reason about.

The public version commits sanitized demo content by default. Private content and private media live in ignored trees, selected only by explicit public/private scripts that generate the active barrel before dev, typecheck, and build.

## Facts

| | |
|---|---|
| **Content** | Typed EN/RU/AR structures, not string-key resources |
| **Publishing** | SPA routes plus generated per-case static heads |
| **Agents** | Text mirrors and llms.txt generated at build time |
| **Telemetry** | Same-origin endpoint, no third-party tracker |

## Architecture

### Public/private content selection

\`\`\`text
npm script -> CONTENT_SOURCE -> select-content.mjs
                         | public/private |
                         v                v
              public demo exports      .private exports
                         \\              /
                          src/content/active.ts
\`\`\`

**Default.** Plain dev/build fail until a public or private script is chosen.

**Private.** Local ignored tree can override copy and media only through explicit private scripts.

### Build outputs

\`\`\`text
typed content -> React UI
             -> public/dev mirrors or private dist mirrors
             -> llms.txt + per-page text mirrors
             -> dist/cases/<slug>/index.html with case head
\`\`\`

**Humans.** SPA stays fast and route-aware.

**Agents.** Text mirrors expose the same case structure without scraping UI.

## Key engineering decisions

### 01 · Typed content over i18n runtime

**Decision.** The site keeps a custom typed content object instead of moving to i18next.

**Why.** The project needs structure, autocomplete, and compile-time locale parity more than plural rules or translation-management workflows.

**Cost.** Adding a third locale later would require another typed content tree.

### 02 · Generated active barrel

**Decision.** Explicit public/private scripts write src/content/active.ts to point at the selected content tree.

**Why.** TypeScript, Vite config, and build-time generators all see the same import path without runtime alias tricks.

**Cost.** The generated file must stay gitignored and created before typecheck/build; plain build/dev intentionally fail instead of guessing.

### 03 · Static head copies for case routes

**Decision.** The build writes dist/cases/<slug>/index.html with case-specific title, description, alternate text links, and JSON-LD.

**Why.** Social scrapers and many bots do not run client JavaScript, so client-only head updates are not enough.

**Cost.** A small Vite plugin owns index.html injection.

## Stack

| | |
|---|---|
| **Frontend** | React · TypeScript · Vite 7 |
| **Design** | CSS custom properties · route-aware case styling |
| **Content** | Generated active barrel · public/private trees |
| **Agents** | Text mirrors · llms.txt · per-case alternates |
| **Analytics** | Node ingest · SQLite · same-origin proxy |
| **CI** | Lint · unit tests · typecheck · build · audit · leakage guards |

## Lessons & status

### Carry forward

- A portfolio can be a proof artifact, not only a brochure.
- Typed content gives better refactor safety than string keys here.
- Agent-readable mirrors make the work inspectable without UI scraping.
- Pure helpers exported from both modules become the natural test surface — Markdown serializers, payload validators, dwell classifier.

### Would change

- Sanitization must include media, not only text.
- Static metadata should be generated before publication.
- CI should guard leakage patterns from the first public push.
- Public proof needs executable checks around mirrors, telemetry validation, and content parity — type signatures alone do not catch array-length drift between EN and RU trees.

Real architecture case with sanitized author-facing copy.

---

Source: https://ilyadev.xyz/cases/portfolio-site (HTML) · /cases/portfolio-site.txt (this file)
Previous: 05 — macOS Network Guard · Demo client → https://ilyadev.xyz/cases/macos-vpn.txt
Index: https://ilyadev.xyz/llms.txt — full case-study list
Author: Demo Author — https://ilyadev.xyz/index.txt
"
`;

exports[`caseStudyToMarkdown — snapshots > EN · roblox-game 1`] = `
"# Roblox Arena · Demo runtime

\`04 · roblox-game · Demo\`

Fictional multiplayer arena slice focused on deterministic combat rules, server authority, and tool-assisted content balancing.

**Scope:** Demo · gameplay systems  
**Role:** Gameplay systems demo with server-owned rules

**Video:** [YouTube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dQw4w9WgXcQ) · [RuTube](https://rutube.ru/video/private/2afc367fc1968ed386e52665ee7a829b/?p=WcFMiE-n0wydU96W_9-nXw)

## Video walkthrough

Demo arena walkthrough: combat, rewards and spawn logic stay server-owned. Designers tune enemies, abilities and economy through structured data tables; telemetry loops feed the next balance pass.

Demo placeholder transcript. The video walks through the public Roblox arena demo — server authority, balance tables, telemetry loops. Replace this transcript when forking the engine with your own content.

---

## Context

> Fun changes fast. Rules still need one authority.

Small multiplayer prototypes often become brittle when gameplay rules leak across client scripts, UI code, and designer experiments. The fictional arena keeps the loop narrow: players fight, earn rewards, unlock variants, and return to a faster next round.

The useful engineering work is less about visual spectacle and more about rule ownership. The server validates combat, rewards, cooldowns, and inventory updates; the client predicts only what can be safely corrected.

## Facts

| | |
|---|---|
| **Surface** | Round-based arena prototype |
| **Rules** | Server-owned damage, rewards, cooldowns |
| **Content** | Enemy and ability tables |
| **Feedback** | Match events, economy sinks, retention hints |

## Architecture

### Authority split

\`\`\`text
Client input -> server rule check -> replicated result -> UI feedback
      prediction        authority          correction       effects only
\`\`\`

**Client.** Feels responsive but does not grant rewards.

**Server.** Owns combat outcomes, drops, and progression.

## Key engineering decisions

### 01 · Server-owned rewards

**Decision.** Rewards are granted only by server rules after validated combat events.

**Why.** Progression bugs are expensive; the economy must not depend on client claims.

**Cost.** More replication code for responsive feedback.

### 02 · Data tables for balance

**Decision.** Enemies, ability numbers, and drop rates live in structured tables.

**Why.** Design iteration should not require code edits for every tuning pass.

**Cost.** Tables need validation so impossible values fail early.

### 03 · Event taxonomy before content scale

**Decision.** Match, reward, failure, and quit events are named before adding more modes.

**Why.** Balance without telemetry becomes guesswork once content grows.

**Cost.** Early naming discipline slows first prototype speed.

## Stack

| | |
|---|---|
| **Runtime** | Roblox services · Luau modules |
| **Rules** | Server combat checks · cooldown registry |
| **Content** | Enemy tables · ability tables · reward tables |
| **Client** | Prediction hints · replicated UI state |
| **Telemetry** | Round events · reward events · quit points |
| **Demo media** | Generic SVG placeholder assets |

## Lessons & status

### Carry forward

- Server authority keeps the economy debuggable.
- Balance tables beat scattered constants.
- Telemetry labels must arrive before content scale.

### Would change

- Prototype validation tools earlier.
- Separate cosmetic unlocks from combat numbers.
- Keep client prediction narrow and disposable.

Fictionalized gameplay case for public repo review.

---

Source: https://ilyadev.xyz/cases/roblox-game (HTML) · /cases/roblox-game.txt (this file)
